Senate Commerce and Labor 1
Amendment No. 1 to SB2155
Bailey
Signature of Sponsor
AMEND S e n ate Bill No. 2155* House Bill No. 2619
by deleting all language after the enacting clause and substituting:
SECTION 1. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 56-7-3706, is amended by deleting
subsections (a) and (b) and substituting:
(a) A prior authorization required for an outpatient healthcare service to treat a
chronic condition of an enrollee remains valid for at least twelve (12) months after the
healthcare professional or provider receives the prior authorization approval, unless the
clinical criteria in § 56-7-3707 provides otherwise.
(b) A prior authorization required for a prescription drug to treat a chronic
condition of an enrollee remains valid for at least twelve (12) months after the healthcare
professional or provider receives the prior authorization approval, unless the clinical
criteria in § 56-7-3707 provides otherwise.
SECTION 2. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 56-7-3703, is amended by adding
the following as a new subsection:
(d)
(1) A healthcare professional with the same education and training as the
healthcare professional requesting the prior authorization of a healthcare service
shall make an adverse determination of medical necessity.
(2) Before making an adverse determination under subdivision (d)(1), the
reviewing healthcare professional must review:
(A) The treating healthcare professional's recommendation;
(B) The enrollee's medical record or other clinical history; and
SA1012
017311
- 1 -

(C) The enrollee's individual clinical circumstances.
(3) A pharmacist may perform a medical necessity determination for any
drug except a specialty drug. As used in this subdivision (d)(3), "specialty drug"
means a high-cost, complex medication that is designed to treat a chronic, rare,
or complex condition.
SECTION 3. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 56, Chapter 7, Part 10, is amended by
adding the following as new sections:
56-7-1022. Credit card payments.
(a) When initiating or changing the type of payment to a healthcare provider
using electronic funds transfer payments, including virtual credit card payments, a health
insurance entity or the health insurance entity's vendor must:
(1) Notify the healthcare provider of any fees associated with a particular
payment method;
(2) Advise the healthcare provider of the available payment methods;
and
(3) Provide clear instructions to the healthcare provider on how to select
an alternative payment method.
(b) A health insurance entity or the health insurance entity's vendor that initiates
or changes the type of payment to a healthcare provider for healthcare electronic funds
transfer and remittance advice transactions under 45 CFR 162.1601 and 45 CFR
162.1602 shall not charge a fee solely to transmit the payment to the healthcare provider
unless the healthcare provider has consented to the fee.
(c) A healthcare provider's agent may charge reasonable fees for transaction
management, data management, portal services, and other value-added services
related to transactions under 45 CFR 162.1601 and 45 CFR 162.1602, in addition to any
bank transmission fee.
56-7-1023. Medical complexity considerations in reimbursement.
- 2 - 017311

A health insurance entity's contracts and reimbursement policies issued,
delivered, entered into, amended, or renewed on or after April 30, 2027, must take into
account a patient's medical complexity and comorbidity and must reimburse healthcare
providers for covered services, procedures, and devices provided to the patient that are
medically necessary.
SECTION 4. Tennessee Code Annotated, Title 56, Chapter 7, is amended by adding
the following as a new part:
56-7-3901. Part definitions.
(a) As used in this part:
(1) "Commissioner" means the commissioner of commerce and
insurance;
(2) "Downcoding":
(A) Means:
(i) The adjustment of a claim submitted to a health
insurance entity to a less complex or lower cost procedure code;
or
(ii) A reduction of billed service levels made by a health
insurance entity, including, but not limited to, diagnosis-related
group assignments, that reduces payment below the amount
originally billed by the healthcare provider; and
(B) Does not mean a recoupment, as defined in § 56-7-110;
(3) "Health insurance entity" has the same meaning as defined in § 56-7-
109; and
(4) "Healthcare provider" has the same meaning as defined in § 56-61-
102 and includes a facility licensed under title 33.
56-7-3902. Prohibition on downcoding insurance claims.
- 3 - 017311

A health insurance entity shall not downcode a claim that contains a current
procedural terminology evaluation and management code submitted by a healthcare
provider unless:
(1) An employee or contractor of the health insurance entity makes the
downcoding determination in accordance with the American Medical
Association's current procedural terminology manual evaluation and
management documentation criteria and the centers for medicare and medicaid
services guidelines for reporting evaluation and management codes, after a
documented clinical review of the medical records supporting the claim; and
(2) The health insurance entity complies with the notification
requirements in § 56-7-3904.
56-7-3903. Protections for patients with chronic conditions.
A health insurance entity shall not use downcoding practices in a targeted or
discriminatory manner against a healthcare provider that routinely treats patients with
complex or chronic conditions.
56-7-3904. Notification requirements for downcoded claims.
(a) A health insurance entity may downcode a claim submitted by a healthcare
provider only after providing notice to the healthcare provider that the entity intends to
downcode the claim, requesting from the healthcare provider the medical records that
support the claim, and reviewing the medical records supporting the claim.
(b) If a health insurance entity intends to downcode a claim, then the health
insurance entity must request from the submitting healthcare provider the medical
records associated with such claim.
(c) A healthcare provider shall submit medical records requested by a health
insurance entity pursuant to subsection (b) within fifteen (15) days after the date of the
request.
- 4 - 017311

(d) A health insurance entity that receives medical records pursuant to
subsection (c) shall send a written acknowledgement of receipt of such records to the
submitting healthcare provider.
(e) A health insurance entity shall pay a claim within twenty-one (21) days after
the date the health insurance entity sends a written acknowledgement of receipt to a
healthcare provider pursuant to subsection (d).
(f) If a healthcare provider does not submit to a health insurance entity the
medical records requested pursuant to subsection (b), then the health insurance entity
may downcode the claim and must provide notice as described in subsection (g).
(g) If a health insurance entity downcodes a claim after reviewing the medical
records, then the health insurance entity must notify the healthcare provider in a
remittance advice that includes:
(1) The specific reasons for the downcoding, including reference to the
clinical criteria used to justify the downcoding;
(2) The original and revised service codes and payment amounts; and
(3) Notice of the right to appeal under § 56-7-3905.
56-7-3905. Appeal process for downcoded claims.
(a) When a health insurance entity downcodes a claim submitted by a
healthcare provider, the health insurance entity must provide the healthcare provider
with:
(1) Electronic notice to the email address listed in the healthcare
provider's contract, or any subsequent contact update made to such contract, of
the right to appeal the portion of the claim that was downcoded;
(2) Instructions on how to file an appeal; and
(3) The name, email address, and telephone number for the individual or
department responsible for the appeal.
- 5 - 017311

(b) The health insurance entity shall acknowledge receipt of an appeal in writing
within five (5) business days after receipt.
(c) A health insurance entity may have multiple levels of appeals, not to exceed
three (3) levels. The determination of at least one (1) level of appeal must be made by a
healthcare professional with the same or a higher level of licensure as the treating
healthcare professional. A health insurance entity shall only downcode a claim after
reviewing the treating healthcare professional's recommendation, the enrollee's medical
record or other clinical history, and the enrollee's individual clinical circumstances.
(d) The health insurance entity shall render a decision on an appeal no later than
thirty (30) days after the date the healthcare provider files the appeal.
(e) If the health insurance entity determines that the claim should not have been
downcoded, then the health insurance entity must pay the healthcare provider within
fifteen (15) business days after the determination with any interest due to the healthcare
provider pursuant to § 56-7-109.
(f) If the health insurance entity fails to render a decision within the thirty-day
time period in subsection (d), then the claim is deemed approved and payable as
originally submitted. The health insurance entity shall pay the healthcare provider within
fifteen (15) days after the expiration of the thirty-day time period in subsection (d).
(g) A healthcare provider may appeal in batches of similar claims involving
substantially similar downcoding issues by a health insurance entity.
(h) If a health insurance entity has a level of appeal that includes arbitration,
then the health insurance entity must not require a healthcare provider to have more
than one (1) arbitrator. Such appeal level must include an option for the healthcare
provider to participate virtually in arbitration.
56-7-3906. Enforcement of part.
(a) The commissioner may assess a civil penalty for a violation of this part in
accordance with § 56-2-305.
- 6 - 017311

(b) This part must be construed to promote prompt and full payment for
healthcare services rendered. A health insurance entity shall not evade, delay, or
otherwise avoid liability under this part through internal procedures, policy language, or
administrative practices.
(c) The commissioner may, upon finding that a contract provision, policy term, or
administrative practice waives, limits, or circumvents the protections of this part, order
such provision to be unenforceable as against public policy.
SECTION 5. If any provision of this act or its application to any person or circumstance
is held invalid, then the invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of the act that
can be given effect without the invalid provision or application, and to that end, the provisions of
this act are severable.
SECTION 6. The headings in this act are for reference purposes only and do not
constitute a part of the law enacted by this act. However, the Tennessee Code Commission is
requested to include the headings in any compilation or publication containing this act.
SECTION 7.
(a) For the purpose of promulgating rules, this act takes effect upon becoming a
law, the public welfare requiring it.
(b) For all other purposes, this act takes effect April 30, 2027, the public welfare
requiring it.
